					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody">Yeah having one direction take over another or having both cancelling is definitely the way to go (do it the more compact way possible without adding code to handle this). You just don't want your programm to crash if up+down or left+right are pressed, so that this enable people to play your game with some emulators or unlicenced controllers without having it crashing.
<br />
<br />Remember, computer science is like math, the more complicated the route you take is, the most likely it's the wrong one.
<br />
<br />BTW pressing up+down+B is the only way to use a subweapon while crouching in Castlevania. And the knife/boomerang thrown IS lower than normal, apparently the developper just didn't think that up+down wasn't possible. Altough this only works for Castlevania 1, not Castlevania 3.</div>

					
